Great. Let's say we have a trait `Drawable`. Instead of inheritance, we compose structs with traits implemented by the component parts.

Here’s an example:

```rust
trait Drawable {
    fn draw(&self);
}

struct Button {
    text: String,
}
impl Drawable for Button {
    fn draw(&self) {
        println!("Button with label {}",&self.text);
    }
}

struct Image {
    src: String,
}
impl Drawable for Image {
    fn draw(&self) {
        println!("Image from {}", &self.src);
    }
}

// Now you can use a struct `App` to compose these:
struct App {
    children: Vec<Box<dyn Drawable>>
}
impl App {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self { children: vec![] }
    }
    pub fn add_child(&mut self, child: Box<dyn Drawable>) {
        self.children.push(child);
    }
}

fn main() {
    let app = App::new();
    app.add_child(Box::new(Button { text: "Click me".to_string() }));
    app.add_child(Box::new(Image { src: "img.png".to_string() }));

    for child in &app.children {
        child.draw();
    }
}
```
This approach lets you compose arbitrary UI components without tight coupling, which is more flexible.

